About
In the oldest house on the hill of Montmartre lived fourteen personalities, among whom Renoir, Valadon, Dufy and Poulbot. Take a step back in time to the glory days of this independent and bohemian quarter through original works by Utrillo, Toulouse-Lautrec and Willette at the Montmartre Museum. The gardens and the atmosphere have a rustic feel to them, making this is a very special site in the heart of Paris.
Duration: 1-2 hours

tk3232
Sugar Land, TX4,269 contributions
Nice, but overpriced
Sep 2023 â¢ Couples
The main goal of our visit to this museum was to see the apartment-studio-workshop of the great and very beloved artist Auguste Renoir. After purchasing tickets (there is no queue and no need to buy in advance), the employee showed us where to start exploring the museum, we needed to climb the steep narrow stairs and voila we are in a modest studio apartment where Renoir lived and worked between 1875-1877 and where he created his early famous works such as "Bal du Moulin de la Galette", "Jardin de la rue Cortot" and "La balanÃ§oire" ("Swing").
This studio is just a one part of the Montmartre museum - after the tour we walked and sat in the gardens, which were restored in memory of Renoir. There is a charming cafe in the garden. Then, after walking through the gardens, we found the entrance from the first house to another part of the museum, this is a permanent exhibition (before entering, continue walking to the end of the short stone path, which offers a great view of the Montmartre vineyard).

The museum's collection of paintings, posters, old photos, music, and memorabilia is split between two 17th-century manor houses. Montmartre's cabaret years come to life here such as the famous Chat Noir poster or Toulouse-Lautrec posters and displays about the biggest and most famous cabaret of all: the cancan-kickers of the Moulin Rouge. The Museum open daily 10 am - 18 pm, good WC, duration approx. 1 h 30 min. My rating is 4 stars, I think that the museum is overpriced (15 euros per adult and it was no special temporary or extra exhibition was there), so once is more than enough to visit this museum.
Written November 16, 2023

The museum is open every day from 10-18h. The adult entrance ticket is 9.50. Tickets may be purchased in advance online, to be printed out at home ticketmaster, Regarding group visits which must be booked in advance. The Subway/Metro will take you to Lamarck-Caulaincourt station in the 18th arrondissement; From there, you walk uphill for about 7 mins. to the lovely museum, or you can wait for a little bus.
